@CNBCFastMoney Presenting the notion of one influence (on markets) is overly simplistic that, moreover, cant be proven. Read Annie Duke's new book, "Thinking in Bets" for more on decision making/results. amazon.com/Thinking-Bets-Mak…

Traders should recognize there are always multi-factored reasons in explaining short term moves. There is no one factor. Some factors are "hidden" and unknowable. Trading/life is more like poker and less like chess (when everything is known). @CNBCFastMoney

The need to explain (with self confidence) every market move in a definitive narrative is to quote a friend of mine, "a fool's errand." The answer is that the markets are a complex mosaic and multi factored. @CNBCFastMoney

So now we all know, definitively, why stocks are moving higher. Buybacks. No, its earnings. Jeez Louise. How about, "I dont know"... or the machines and algos are following initial momentum? @CNBCFastMoney
@CNBCFastMoney The reason S&P earnings revisions moved higher this year is firmly implanted in tax reform. And that is a one time event.
